title.narrative: 601 SOCIAL PROTECTION PROGRAMMES FOR CHILDREN, ADOLESCENTS AND THEIR FAMILIES

description.narrative: National, UNICEF programming state governments and other partners have adequate capacity to plan, integrate, implement and monitor social protection programmes for children, adolescents and their families especially addressing marginalized and vulnerable at most critical stages of life cycle and vulnerable situations (*urban slums, climate change impacts, insurgencies) by 2022, which contributes to Access To Inclusive Social Protection, Access To Inclusive Social Protection (Covid), Communication And Advocacy, Cross-Sectoral - Human Rights, Cross-Sectoral - Other Programme Areas, Evaluation, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Reducing Child Poverty, Reducing Child Poverty (Covid), Research. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Social policies and strategies inform more effective and efficient planning, budgeting and implementation of social service programmes for reducing inequities and gender inequalities especially for the most vulnerable and marginalized children and adolescents by 2022

description.narrative: To mitigate the COVID-19 related socio-economic impact on children, UNICEF successfully positioned Cash Plus approach and discourse around shock-responsive SP backed by robust evidence pieces in partnership with NITI Aayog. In 10 states, UNICEF supported drafting of Child Care- Cash Plus scheme for orphans (victims of Covid-19) covering 30468 children by oct-2021. Efforts continued to ensure that SP entitlements reached the ‘last-mile’ children and women using multiple technology/community platforms. Two large-scale schemes, PMMVY shows a decline of -3% in UNICEF states, against the national average of -12% and NREGS an ;improvement of ;84% as ;against national average | Status:On-track | As-of Date:04/01/2022
